@flexiarg collaboration-coherence/stasis
@title Find the Moving Dimension; Don't Confuse a Stuck Axis with a Stuck Project
@keywords stasis, stuck, dimension, balanced-progress, carrying-capacity, perceived-stuck
@audience peer-learning facilitators, project leads, contributors who feel stuck
@tone reflective
@style pattern
@references [peeragogy/carrying-capacity collaboration-coherence/magical-thinking peeragogy/roadmap]

! conclusion: Apparent stasis in a multi-dimensional project is almost always a single dimension having stopped while others remain available; the failure mode is identifying with the stuck dimension and concluding the whole project is stuck.  The pattern is to identify which dimensions are actually moving, work deliberately on those, and accept the stuck dimension as out-of-reach for now (rather than spending energy on the dimension where progress is most expensive).  This is "find the moving dimension," not "force the stuck one."
  + context: Voluntary, distributed projects routinely encounter dimensions on which progress slows to zero — a maintainer who can't find time, a tool that won't ship, a funder who won't decide, a contributor who has stepped back.  When a project's identity has crystallised around the stuck dimension (e.g. "we're the project that's waiting for X"), the felt experience is total stasis even though most of the project is still movable.  Living systems, the source notes, are never really in stasis; what is happening is that one or more dimensions of life are moving very slowly.  The grilled-cheese-sandwich metaphor catches it: even a balanced diet has individual foods that aren't on the menu today.
  + TENSION:
    Axis: pursuing the stuck dimension ↔ rotating to a moving one.
    Real: the stuck dimension might be load-bearing — abandoning it forfeits something the project needs.  Pursuing it might be the only path forward.  Equally, pursuing it past the point of diminishing returns starves dimensions where progress is cheaper.  Both forces operate continuously.
    Irreducible: a project cannot simultaneously be patient with a stuck dimension and treat its stuckness as the project's defining state.  Patience requires the project to keep moving on other dimensions.
    Active: the pull recurs whenever a contributor looks at the project and sees the stuck-thing first; when frustration converts to identity ("we are the people waiting for X"); when fresh energy shows up and gets routed to the stuck dimension instead of a moving one.
  + COMPOSITIONS:
    (1) Dimension inventory: enumerate the project's current dimensions (technical, social, content, infrastructure, external relations) and rate each for current movement.  The act of enumeration usually surfaces moving dimensions the contributor had stopped seeing.
    (2) Deliberate rotation: choose one moving dimension to focus on for a defined period; deliberately don't pursue the stuck one.  The constraint is the discipline.
    (3) Stuck-dimension monitor: maintain a low-cost watch on the stuck dimension (per-quarter check-in, named monitor) so the project notices when it becomes movable again, without letting it dominate attention while it remains stuck.
    (4) Identity decoupling: state explicitly that the project is not defined by its stuck dimension.  This is harder than it sounds — the stuck dimension is often the most-discussed thing precisely because it isn't moving.
    (5) Carrying-capacity respect: stasis on one dimension is often a carrying-capacity symptom on a contributor (they're maxed out on something else, including life).  Pair with peeragogy/carrying-capacity rather than treating stasis as project failure.
  + CHECK:
    Engaged when: the project can name at least one dimension it's currently making progress on, and the stuck dimension is monitored without dominating attention.  Failing when: every internal conversation returns to the stuck dimension, or the project's identity has merged with what it's waiting for.
  + FAILURE-MODES:
    - Stuck-dimension identification: the project's self-description leads with what it's waiting for ("we're stuck on X") rather than what it's doing now.
    - Misallocated energy: fresh contributor energy is repeatedly routed to the stuck dimension where it bounces; the moving dimensions have no one assigned to them.
    - Felt-total-stasis: the perceived stuckness is total even though external observers can name multiple moving dimensions.  The discrepancy is itself diagnostic.
    - Carrying-capacity exhaustion masquerading as stasis: a single contributor's bandwidth limit reads to the project as the project being stuck.  See peeragogy/carrying-capacity for the disambiguation.
    - Premature pivot: under stasis felt as total, the project pivots — abandoning the moving dimensions along with the stuck one.  The opposite failure mode of stuck-dimension identification, but produced by the same misreading.
